< review>
Ole's alignment is my go to shop for suspension and brakes needs. Very reasonably priced and they will get the job done. They might be a little old school, but that's what is best about them. They get it right, old or new. They even straightened a utility trailer axle when I was told by several places it couldn't be done. Also, You can take your own parts and they will work with you. They are closed Friday and weekends but it's worth the time to schedule for mon- Thursday work. You can even drop car off night before, they will work with you :)<//review>

<Text>On a trip to Houston from SF.  Thursday I thought something was wrong with my brakes because of a new noise.  Just happened to be in Yucca taking the scenic route.  Saw Ole's and pulled in.  He checked my brakes, found nothing, but found a screw in my tire and that there was some play in the wheel.  Told me it was the bearings going bad.  Advised me to buy the part and get it fixed before traveling more.  Ole did not charge me anything for the brake check and he didn't tell me I needed new brakes when I didn't. He suggested another tire shop to remove the screw and patch the tire.  See AA Tire & Muffler.  See my review.  They told me the same thing about the bearings.  It was too late to get work done, but I bought the part. Checked with another place at 7:00 the next morning.  Told me it would be around 1:00 and cost me $240 for labor because of rust on the undercarriage. Came back to Ole's at 8:00.  He fixed it in under an hour and charged me $60.  This got us back on the road to Houston without too much lost time.  If we had waited until Monday, we would have needed to turn around and head back to SF.  I would use Ole's anytime I could if I was in the area.  May have him do some more work when we go back through the area.  Thanks Ole.</Text><Pics>None<//Pics><response>None</response><Gmap_id>0x80db27e627d1240f:0x98aa01080831ae72<//Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>

<Text>Decided to give this place a try and was not to satisfied. Went it and the place is decorated very nice with Mexican pictures the waitress was very nice and helpful. She brought us chips and salsa which were good. The menu was big it had many different Mexican dishes so I decided to go for tacos de buche aka pork stomach tacos and a michelada. She comes back and say they were out of buches so I went with an all meat carne asada wet burrito and my wife went for a combination carne wet burrito.  We received the burritos and saw that my wife's combination burrito was bigger than all meat carne asada burrito. I told the waitress why is her burrito bigger and she said it was because I got the all meat burrito so its smaller. I'm thinking  to myself I paid extra to get an all meat burrito and it's smaller than the combination burrito which don't make any sense because im paying extra but I didnt argue with the waitress and ate the burrito. The burrito was okay but the meat was way too salty, and my wife who is a person that likes salty thought it was way too salty for her. Well at least I had my michelada which was okay. I just felt for a michelada it needed some more of that clamato mix. My wife had an horchata thinking it was going to be fresh homemade horchata but It was the same  horchata you get from El Pollo Loco. The waitress which was nice came back and said how was everything and we told her the burrito was salty. She went out back and came back and said that the chef tasted the carne asada and it was salty so they were going to take the drinks of the bill. Something is something I guess. Overall I probably won't come back to this place again. I wouldnt say it's nasty and don't come because the service was good and it looks like they have very good happy hour deals, but the Mexican food was not up to my standards.</Text><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNjAaRASnoY-z-hmKBeqcvyJMPsGiTpDy8afenE=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics>< resp>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
I found Sac Notary Services on Google, "open" on a late Sunday afternoon. I called ahead to verify that it was indeed open. Convenient location in south Sacramento along a row of storefront with easy parking.
I needed a verification of signature. Naveen commented that I had all the sections on my form filled and completed, thus making a quick process.
Of course, he charged the Secretary of the State's published rate. Because he has a storefront, no "additional" charges, like a mobile notary would have charged. If I have a need for another notary service in the future, I will skip the "shipping business" stores, and return to Naveen at Sac Notary!<//text>

<UserId.>117781923068235783037</UserId.><name>kim Smith< /name><time>1464635748570</time><rate>5< /rate>< review>
My family and I have been going to this precious jewel for a couple of months.  I found it through a friend of mine who recommend it to me.  The atmosphere is excellent.  The food is fantastic because it is farm-to-fork and they change the menu 4 times per year accordingly to the season.  The staff members are friendly and they know the menu very well.  The drinks are fantastic and refreshing.

They have a private room called "Churchill Room" because the big portrait of Winston Churchill.  I had  plenty of business meetings in that room.  It is quiet, private and it has access to connect your computer to their TV for a presentation.

If you look at it from the outside it looks different to the inside.  It is a beautiful place inside.  A long Bar with nice tables and plenty of TV's and if you do not like music or TV's while you are dining, they have a section that has neither.

The people who recommend it to me was right about this place.  Now my family and I do not have to travel to downtown Sacramento, Folsom  or Roseville area for a good  dinning experience.  We have Stirling Bridges.</review>

<Name>Rachell Grant< /Name><response>None<//response><date>1488728070104</date><user>107167046792527541879< /user>< Gmap_id>
0x809adee8c2f1e337:0x9cd87f5671b04036< /Gmap_id>
< Pics>
None<//Pics>
<Rating>3< /Rating>< review>
I'm so torn on this place. I have fond memories of driving here after work when it first opened; enjoying the atmosphere while sipping a beer and thinking, "wow this place is unlike any other place in the neighborhood". Sadly those days are fading away.

I went here just last Thursday and was sorely disappointed. The service was great, the girl with red hair and glasses was so funny and full of personality. However the food is lacking. They served toasted (I use that term lightly) white sandwich bread with our artichoke dip.
Making it hard to scoop up the dip since the bread was still soft in the middle. It lacked the crunch that I associate with artichoke dip. Lastly our pizza was burned right down the center. I smothered it in ranch to hide the taste.

My friend and I camped at a table for a few hours (they were not busy) and caught up. At some point we had to ask our server if they could turn the music down. Far too loud for a not so busy place. Before we left we visited the ladies room. We were disappointed at the condition of the bathrooms. 1 out of the 5 stalls was safe to use. After taking turns to do our business we hurriedly got our jackets and left.

As we walked outside I noticed that were was a "notice in change of ownership" sign posted outside. I surely do hope that's a sign of good things to come for this place.< /review>

<text>We are regular customers at Stirling Bridges since it opened.  We love the atmosphere and the great supply of beer.  Lately, however, we have disappointed with the food.  The beef stroganoff used to served with fettuccini.  Same with the chicken alfredo.  Some time ago they switched the pasta to cavatappi, and it's just not the same.  We no longer order those items.  My other gripe is that too often the food comes out lukewarm - - not hot!  Last night the corned beef, cabbage and redskin potatoes were not hot.  A week or so ago the lobster ravioli was not hot.  A month or two ago the seafood special was salmon.  I ordered it, and it came out hot, but the two sides, rice and vegetables, were lukewarm.  A couple months ago I had the sliced tri-tip French dip and the meat was very gristly.  I still like the place for the atmosphere, but the food right now is mediocre.  Walter L.< /text>< Pictures>

I really do hate leaving a bad review for this company because at the end of the day they fixed my vehicle and at a reasonable price. Still,  I can't shake the idea that though they are extremely nice that they cannot fully be trusted.

I contacted AAMCO because I thought I was having transmission issues with my vehicle... It would not go into gear. In fact, when I talked to the staff here I first mentioned that I may have a transmission issue. Staff went out of their way to accommodate my vehicle showing up after regular business hours. They also diagnosed my problem for free. These are the only reasons I gave two stars rather than one.

The next day, I was told that my transmission was indeed out and would cost $4,500 to repair. I explained that I might just give up the vehicle and they kept pushing me to take out loans and find other ways to be creative about making the payment. During one of these conversations one of the workers slipped and mentioned to me that the strap was broken on the steering and should only cost a couple of hundred dollars to get fixed. when I mention why I would not just do this then he backtracked and said that this broken strap was indicative of a transmission problem. They also told me that I had seven transmission codes.

At this point, I still believed they were being honest. However, I decided to see if auto shops near my home what cost less than in Oceanside. however, when I called the shops near my home they were thoroughly surprised that I was quoting a transmission replacement even though my strap was broken. One person specifically told me that a strap can be replace for $200 and that a broken strap has nothing to do with the transmission.

I called another shot to verify this information. This third shop also told me that a broken strap will lead to no codes for transmission. They told me that they would only recommend replacing the transmission if I had a few hundred transmission codes stored.

I was extremely upset with AAMCO for misleading me and making me believe that my vehicle need a new transmission in order to run properly. Because I live an hour away I could not simply come and pick up my vehicle. I decided that my only options were to either tow it to a different shop or allow them to repair the strap.

I then called them and explained that I would have the money for the transmission in a couple of weeks. I told them that if we could fix the strap today that I would come back for the transmission. They fixed this strap for about $550 (I had other oceanside bids for about this amount). I picked the vehicle up the next day... again, I am unsure if I can trust this company. It seems to me that they were being misleading on purpose. I will never go back.

One more thing I should mention... I was told that I would be given a military discount as I am a disabled veteran. This was not honored. Supposedly though, the $550 price included a 10% discount for using cash.</review>

<Rate>5<//Rate><review>Had to get my transmission rebuilt on my 96 Dodge Ram 1500 this last month.  First local place I took it too in Carlsbad said they wouldn't rebuild (even though they weren't sure if it was just a part of the transmission that needed work or the whole thing) and pushed me towards spending $3k to get replace the whole thing with a used one, no warranty.

My friend suggested I get someone else to check it out as it could just be a part of the transmission, rather than replace the whole thing.

Decided to give AAMCO a try.  Jimmy was my contact at AAMCO and was straightforward with me from the get go explaining everything.  They found out nothing mechanically was wrong with the transmission, just a few parts needed to be re-built, not the whole thing.

They had me back on the road in 2 days and gave me a 1-year warranty on their work.

Saved me some cash, were honest and upfront and got me back on the road quickly.  Couldn't ask for much better.

Truck is running great!< /review>< Pictures>

<UserId.>107440799392003639178<//UserId.>< Name>
Jeffrey Quinn< /Name>
< Time>
1402682887733<//Time>
<Rating>1< /Rating>< Text>
I am writing this review to help prevent others from suffering the same aggravation I suffered as a customer of AAMCO in Oceanside, CA. I have been building Jeep Wranglers for Off Road use for the last 16 years. I am currently in my 5th Project build a 2008 Jeep JK.   I noticed my Clutch was starting to fail and didn't desire to spend a few nights at the hobby shop on base as I have a new born at home. I brought my Jeep in to AAMCO Oceanside.  The Owner Ben was very friendly and supportive of the Military, and made me feel like I would be taken good care of.  He said it would be a day maybe two to replace the Clutch on Monday.  Well Friday comes around and after repeated calls for updates that were never returned I finally get my Jeep. Everything appeared to be in working order other than some Transmission fluid on the bottom of the Transmission.  I just wrote this off to them not cleaning up well.  Two weeks later, after having driven less than 300 miles. I noticed a dripping leak running down from the top of the Transmission. I begin to investigate the cause, and trace the drip to the Shift Tower.  I removed the center console and discover that the Shift Boot and foam Buffers had not been re-installed properly, as well as the clip on the Shift Boot had been broken.   I removed the foam ring and Shift tower foam Buffer (which was soaked in fluid) to find there was a large dent in the body from Shift tower coming in contact with the body re-installing the transmission. The impact with the body caused one of the mounting bolts on the Shift tower to snap, and broke the seal leading to the leak during operation of the vehicle.  I resealed the Shift Tower temporarily fixing the leak.  Minus the bolt still stuck in the Transmission housing as I did not have to correct extractor at the time.  Having had corrected the issue myself as I needed the Vehicle for work the following morning.  I chose not to pursue the issue with AAMCO Oceanside because of the potential for argument that I damaged it doing the work to fix it myself. You can read more on my experience if you go to YELP as I am out of space on google.<//Text>

< Review>
I have been a loyal AAMCO cusotmer for years, having had a number of major services done, such as transmission rebuild, radiator, water pump, starter, alternator, battery replacement, and smaller jobs such as oil changes and tire rotations. Needing pads and rotors again, due to many miles and my hard driving, I was disapointed to find out that my warranty had expired and I was faced with paying full price to have them replaced once again. Be prepared to be abandoned after some untruthful promises.
On August 17th, 2020, I applied to Ladera Lending, Inc. for a refinance of my mortgage, via Lending Tree. I was assigned LOAN OFFICER Sean Matthews. Upon 라pproval (which should have been impossible prior to satisfactory appraisal) my loan was assigned ID #.

Mr. Mathews inflated the requested loan amount and property value. I assumed he knew what he was doing. He always sounded supremely confident in a perfect outcome.

When the appraisal came in as catastrophically low, I asked for Mr. Mathews help, sending him an appraisal from my last refinance in 2014 explaining that such low appreciation ($5K) is very unlikely due to not only the passage of 6 years, but also such improvements as a new roof and two newly remodeled bathrooms. Mr. Mathews replied that he may have 랍ome options for me, and will I be available by phone today?. I responded that I was available but would appreciate having 랎he options in writing. The options in writing never materialized. Instead, I received an email in which Mr. Mathews (now I understand: UNTRUTHFULLY) promised that he was 랋utting together a rebuttal to the erroneous appraisal right now. He also stated he felt: 랑e have a fair chance of getting a revised appraisal. After that all responses from Ladera CEASED. No more of my messages we answered by Mr. Mathews or Evelyn Dimapilis (Processor, assigned to my application). Ms. Dimapilis must also have been instructed to not acknowledge me any longer?

When my rate-lock was allowed to expire without any response from Ladera, I sent one last email requesting that if Mr. Mathews & Ms. Dimapilis no longer could/wanted to do business, Ladera should please, AT LEAST, WITHDRAW THE CREDIT INQUIRY(S), AND TAKE STEPS TO SAFEGUARD MY PERSONAL AND FINANCIAL INFORMATION. < Text>

Then a lender I had called first returned my call, wooed me back with a cash out refi (I had 2 mortgages) and I switched. It was a really bad move on my part because they ultimately kept dragging their feet so I bailed out of the 2nd lender and called Jeff Yubeta at Ladera back, and asked if we could start again with the cash out refi, and he got me an EVEN BETTER rate, and everything was happy and joyful. <Rating>1</Rating>< Review>
I see that several people had positive experiences with Ladera Lending. My experience was on the opposite end of the spectrum. I have been told that we were at the finish line and ready to close since December. Initially my rep was responsive and on the ball. As we moved through the process I was told that they needed 1 or 2 more items to close several times. Each time I submitted what was asked for within hours and didn't receive any reply for days. I would have to call for updates and at times still took days to get back to me. It is a frustrating experience to say the least. Finally they came back with stipulations that made no sense for what was happening with the home. The loan was to do home improvements, and a s stipulations to fund they wanted a wall that was set to be removed to be painted, and for carpet to be laid in rooms that we're set to be sanded and painted. I turned in the work order to show that all of this work was set to be completed but it made no sense to spend money to complete things that would have to be removed as soon as the loan was funded. They also asked that I pay for a 2nd opinion on the appraisal. They we're the ones who chose the initial appraiser so if they don't trust his appraisal after I was forced to spend $500 with who they selected I shouldn't be on the hook for a 2nd opinion. In closing I was told if I did XYZ that we could move forward with closocl several times. The final straw was the redundant repairs that they wanted completed before funding, and requiring me to pay for a 2nd opinion on an appraisal that they selected the appraiser. I refused to spend more money because for 2 months I was promised a closing that never happened and there was no garunrtee on a closing date even if I did complete these steps. I feel like I wasted time and money and I wish that I would have went with another lender out of the gate, because now I am back at square 1 having to start the process all over again with a new lender.<//Review>

< Review>
When I decided to refinance the house, I jumped on line and entered my information, including the fact I'm a vet,  into a mortgage information provider. They said they would forward my information to 5 lenders. Ha! Try 20. However, it was well worth the aggravation of dealing with all those phone calls and emails, because in the end I found Patrick Creavy of Ladera Lending.

A couple of the lenders offered decent interest rates and plenty of information. Fortunately, Patrick came on board before I actually signed with one of them. The other two lenders told me the VA funding fee was a waste of money. Patrick explained the Interest Rate Reduction Refinance Loan (IRRRL) program associated with the VA. If, at any point, interest rates fall, a vet can apply for an IRRRL. No appraisal, no title fees, no income verification. It's just a lowering of the rate. I was furious at first. I had purchased my home with a VA loan initially. I had refinanced 3 times for the sole purpose of lowering the interest rate. Every one of those financial institutes had talked me out of VA. The initial refinance had not told me about IRRRL. Why would they? Less money in their pocket. When I expressed this to Patrick, he assured me it wasn't deliberate. Most lenders do not specialize in VA, and are therefore ignorant of the benefits. Their ignorance cost me more than $28,000.

Patrick is friendly, honest, and knowledgeable. He believes in communication, and kept me abreast during the entire process. I  am amazed by the quality of his customer service; he's one in a million. I now consider him my personal loan advisor. I have been distributing his cards to friends and family. Need I say more?I would recommend him to anyone, but especially to veterans.< /Review>

<time>1455327290599<//time>< Text>
I am writing this review of Loan Officer Brian Brown.

I used Brian when my wife and I purchased our home in northern CA.  He is easily one of the most knowledgeable and skilled loan officers I have ever dealt with.  The biggest thing that sticks out is that he is ALWAYS available.  I have dealt with loan officers in the past that "just stepped out" or don't return your calls and nothing is more annoying when you have a question or want to know the progress of your loan.  I have found that Brian is easy to get ahold of and returns my calls faster than expected.

I also know that Brian was able to get me THE BEST rate available.  I compared his rates to several other banks and two credit unions and he beat them hands down.  I have referred seven of my friends and two of my bosses to him and he has consistently performed as promised.  As you know, you would never take a chance referring your boss to someone that you didn't have full confidence in.

One of my friends I referred to him was hesitant to call because he wasn't ready to get a loan just yet.  I told him to call anyways and ask Brian questions about what he needed to do in preparation of getting a loan.  Brian talked to him for almost 30 minutes, knowing he wasn't going to be doing a loan for him, but just to give him the information he needed.  Impressive.

In all fairness, he does seem to ask for more documentation than other loan officers have in the past, but I believe that is because he wants to make sure he has all his "ducks in a row" and can put out any potential fires before they begin.  I'll gladly spend an extra 30 minutes gathering docs he needs to save THOUSANDS or TENS OF THOUSANDS of dollars over the life of my loan.

If I can add one more reason on why you should use this specific loan officer - NO SURPISE CHARGES at doc signing.

He's also completed my refi about 6 months ago.  Again, wonderful experience.  Give him a call, you won't be disappointed.<//Text>

<Review>I was referred to Chris Coble by another party who contacted me to see if I was interested in refinancing my home.  I was not in the market for refinancing options because we plan on selling our house within the next two years and plus I didn뗪 want to reduce the equity we had in the house and pay less on principle each month.  So let뗩 just say I wasn뗪 very interested in talking about refinancing at all well that was until I spoke to Chris.  I mentioned the above concerns to Chris and he understood my concerns and told me that he could save me $200-$400 a month on my mortgage payment.   While not decreasing the equity in my home significantly by utilizing the VA refinancing options, and there is a possibility we wouldn뗪 have to make payments for the first two months.  Chris volunteered to send me some numbers that reflected our conversation, I also did my own mortgage amortization calculations and came up with very similar numbers.  At that point I decided to do move forward with VA refinancing option, thanks to Chris.  I뗤 a hard person to convince and live by the motto DTA (Don뗪 Trust Anyone).  So for Chris to get me to trust him in getting us the best rate and options for our mortgage is a testament to him and his dedication to his profession.

So, then begins the process of submitting documents and filling out applications.  Compared to our first mortgage process this one was very streamlined and a majority of it was completed online, without having to leave the comfort of my home, matter of fact I never had to leave my home to complete any portion of the process.  Chris was there every step of the way, following up via email, text and or telephone.  We probably spoke more via text than any other communication means, which I preferred.  If it wasn뗪 for the VA taking its time we probably would have had the entire process completed within 30 days, however the government being the government it took a little longer (approximately 60 days from application submittal to closing).

The time we had schedule for closing was right around Christmas and New Years, and we didn뗪 plan on being in town during this time and would be out of the state visiting family.  I thought this would put a delay in our process but Chris and his company scheduled a Notary to come to the location where we were vacationing to sign our documents.  However, we were unable to close while on vacation due to the aforementioned delays at the VA.  So we closed within the comforts of our home two days after returning for vacation, we got a great rate, I think we pay about $325 less a month, we pay pretty much the same amount to principle and the balance on the loan only went up about $3500.  I would recommend Chris to anyone of my friends looking to refinance or looking to acquire a mortgage for a new purchase.  When we are looking for our new home in the next year or so, we will definitely be contacting Chris for assistance with another mortgage.</Review>< pics>
